05168nam a22008415i 9780520353633DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203536337 a10.1525/97805203536332doi  a(DE-B1597)569530  a(OCoLC)1198929405  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB3318.E88 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a193qOCoLC220/eng/202302161 aLowith, Karl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNietzsche's Philosophy of the Eternal Recurrence of the Same /cKarl Lowith.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword to the English Translation -- tTranslator's Introduction -- tForeword to the First Edition -- tForeword to the Second Edition -- t1. Nietzsche's Philosophy: A System in Aphorisms -- t2. The Division of Nietzsche's Writings into Periods -- t3. The Unifying Fundamental Idea in Nietzsche's Philosophy -- t4. The Anti-Christian Repetition of Antiquity on the Peak of Modernity -- t5. "How One Becomes What One Is" in the Idea of the Eternal Recurrence -- t6. The Problematic Connection between the Existence of Man and the Being of the World in the History of Modern Philosophy -- t7. The Eternal Recurrence of the Same and the Repetition of the Selfsame -- t8. The Critical Yardstick for Nietzsche's Experiment -- tAppendix. On the History of the Interpretation of Nietzsche (1894-1954) -- tReferences -- tAuthor's Notes -- tTranslator's Notes -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis long overdue English translation of Karl Löwith's magisterial study is a major event in Nietzsche scholarship in the Anglo-American intellectual world. Its initial publication was extraordinary in itself—a dissident interpretation, written by a Jew, appearing in National Socialist Germany in 1935. Since then, Löwith's book has continued to gain recognition as one of the key texts in the German Nietzsche reception, as well as a remarkable effort to reclaim the philosopher's work from political misappropriation.For Löwith, the centerpiece of Nietzsche's thought is the doctrine of eternal recurrence, a notion which Löwith, unlike Heidegger, deems incompatible with the will to power. His careful examination of Nietzsche's cosmological theory of the infinite repetition of a finite number of states of the world suggests the paradoxical consequences this theory implies for human freedom. How is it possible to will the eternal recurrence of each moment of one's life, if both this decision and the states of affairs governed by it appear to be predestined? Löwith's book, one of the most important, if seldom acknowledged, sources for recent Anglophone Nietzsche studies, remains a central text for all concerned with understanding the philosopher's work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEternal return. 0aResemblance (Philosophy). 4a19th century. 4aFriedrich Nietzsche. 4aNietzsche. 4ahistory of philosophy. 4ahistory of western philosophy. 4aphilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  acareful examination.  acosmological theory.  aeternal recurrence of the same.  aeternal recurrence.  aexistentialist philosophy.  afree will.  agreat thinkers.  ahistory of philosophy.  ahuman condition.  ahuman creativity.  ahuman freedom.  ahumanity.  ainfinite repetition.  aintellectual world.  amodern philosophy.  amodernity.  anietzsche.  aphilosophy.  apolitical misappropriation.  apredestination.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Arch